I'd say to add a really small example instead of ask developers to check the `processors.py` module. What about something like:
```python
class ProcessorExample(object):
    def process_trace(self, trace):
        # write here your logic to return the `trace` or None;
        # `trace` instance is owned by the thread and you can alter
        # each single span if needed
```

Or something similar, because I still prefer a really concise snippet rather than long sentences. What do you think?

nice :) do you think you could wrap it to a function like:
```python
def get_macro_from_template(name, template, app=None, ctx=None):
    ctx = ctx or {}
    app = app or current_app
    tpl = app.jinja_env.get_template(template)
    macro = getattr(tpl.make_module, name)
    return unicode(macro(**ctx))
```

This is not the best practice to set the `NAME` to the name of last bam file and then override it below if more than one bam file is given.

Add this to the if below:

    {% else %}
        NAME = {{ bam[0].bam.file }}

and remove this line

@jdavies-st is correct. When you are mixing FITS and gwcs you have to take care of 0- vs 1- based coordinates. The gwcs transform is 0-based. However, the values of crpix are 1-based. If you change the CRPIX values to be 0-based, i.e. subtract 1 from them , you will get agreement (you'll get better agreement in the forward direction too). 

BTW, the header has incorrect FITS WCS to start with. It is not allowed to mix CD matrix and CDELT values and in this case the CDELT values are ignored and assumed to be 1.

I don't want to encourage changes and "fixes" to these functions as I think it's time to implement full conversion between the two objects.

It isn't an "unwritten rule" -- it was just the pattern I adopted when moving the API method-specific bits to the connection class.

I did have a thought about the pattern, based on looking at how the gRPC stuff is [organized]https://cloud.google.com/pubsub/reference/rpc/):  ISTM that we might split the API-specific methods into helper objects (matching the `IAMPolicy`, `Publisher`, and `Subscriber` entities on that page).  The "connection" object would then have properties which returned instances of those helpers.  In gRPC, those helpers correspond to the service-specific stubs.

@dhermes WDYT?

Representing functions with mangled strings is unnecessary in Rust. It would be more idiomatic to replace the contents of this block with:
```c
                w(g, ", ");
                write_varname(g, v->function);
```

